



The moshassuck river flows 8.9 miles from the town of Lincoln Rhode Island to the city of Providence. My site, along the river in pawtucket, starts at a spillway near Smithfield and grotto ave, the end of a drain tunnel, meant to push rain water and runoff into the moshassuck river. There were no signs of wildlife from my visit, but often manhaden migrate along the river. The drain has been at risk from the surrounding industrial infrastuctures since the 17th century, and was even the cause of a cholera outbreak in 1849, soon after they build seperate sewage systems. This project maps sonically the acoustics and ambiance of the river and visually the layers of the hidden spillway and drain tunnel. Through field notes, audio video and drawings, this project presents a comprehensive analysis of the all saints drain spillway. 


